text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!L Rhotacism in Japanese English%0a%0a:Author: Russell_E%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aAn instance of avoiding discrimination in the world of chess streaming.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aLink: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yAUtOTA6--A%0a%0aThis clip is actually an instance of avoiding discrimination, and it’s rather lighthearted. The phenomenon is rhotacism of /l/ in Japanese English. %0a%0aThe situation in the clip is a bit more complicated than it seems if you don’t know who the people are. International Master Levy “GothamChess” Rozman is a native speaker of General American English, and speaks a few other languages. Grandmaster Hikaru Nakamura is half-Japanese, and he grew up with his white American mother and Sri Lankan-American stepfather in the USA. He is a native speaker of General American English. He is not a native speaker of Japanese, but he learned to speak some after childhood. So, Hikaru himself has never used /l/-rhotacism naturally. In this situation, the relationship between language and race is quite complicated.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210506-170238-755280#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!"r" and "l" in Japanese %0a-> - kyuwonW%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aIn Japanese, no sound sounds exactly like "r" or "l". Japanese  "r" sounds can be represented with ら (ra) り (ri) る (ru) れ (re) and ろ (ro), and to pronounce these syllables, the tip of the tongue should touch the back of the upper teeth. These syllables all also sound like in between the English "r" or "l", and Japanese does not necessarily distinguish the two sounds in their native language. Therefore, they can pronounce "r" with "l" or "l" with "r".  Along with rhotacism of /l/ in Japanese English, "r" can be pronounced as an "l" like in the word "difference" [ˈdɪfərəns] to [ˈdɪfələns].%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210506-170238-755280#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: E:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
